Asian Dramas Recommendation System¶

The core of this project centers around a thorough analysis of diverse tags and genres, allowing for accurate recommendations of drama names that align with users' interests, derived from their past viewing history of similar dramas.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import re
import requests
import nltk
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS
from PIL import Image

from nltk.stem.snowball import SnowballStemmer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity

Data Scrapping¶

During the project, I conducted web scraping on MyDramaList's top shows to gather pertinent data like titles, release years, countries, genres, and tags. Subsequently, I compiled all the acquired information into a convenient CSV file for further analysis and processing.

dramalist = []

url = "https://mydramalist.com/shows/top"
response = requests.get(url)
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, "html.parser")
lastPage = [a.attrs.get('href') for a in soup.select(".last > a")]
lastNumPage = lastPage[0].split("=")[1]
    
def GetDrama(url):
    response = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, "html.parser")
    dramas = soup.select("h6.title")
    details = soup.select("span.text-muted")
    link = [a.attrs.get('href') for a in soup.select(".film-cover a")]
    
    for index in range(0, len(dramas)):
        detail = details[index].get_text()
        year = re.search('-(.*?),', detail).group(1)
        data = DramaLookup(year, link[index])
        list.append(data)

def DramaLookup(year, link):    
    response2 = requests.get("https://mydramalist.com" + link)
    soup2 = BeautifulSoup(response2.text, 'html.parser')
    
    synopsis = soup2.select(".show-synopsis p")
    synopsis = [s.text for s in synopsis]
    cleanSynopsis = re.sub('\W+', ' ', synopsis[0])
    
    aka = soup2.select(".mdl-aka-titles a")
    aka2 = [a.text for a in aka]
    aka = (', '.join(aka2))
    
    genre = soup2.select(".show-genres a")
    genre2 = [g.text for g in genre]
    genre = (', '.join(genre2))
    
    tags = soup2.select(".show-tags span a")
    tags2 = [t.text for t in tags]
    tags = (', '.join(tags2))
    
    selectDetails = soup2.select(".box:nth-of-type(2) > .box-body > ul > li")
    sd = [sd.text for sd in selectDetails]
    details = {}
    for i in range(0, len(sd)):
        text = sd[i].split(':', 1)
        details[text[0]] = text[1]
    
    selectStats = soup2.select(".box:nth-of-type(3) > .box-body > ul > li")
    ss = [ss.text for ss in selectStats]
    for i in range(0, len(ss)):
        text2 = ss[i].split(':', 1)
        details[text2[0]] = text2[1]
        
    w2wSelect = soup2.select(".wts a b")
    w2w2 = [ww.text for ww in w2wSelect]
    w2w = (', '.join(w2w2))
    
    cncSelect = [a.attrs.get('title') for a in soup2.select(".credits .p-a-0 > a")]
    cnc = (', '.join(cncSelect))
    
    try:
        score = re.search('\d.\d', details["Score"]).group(0)
    except AttributeError:
        score = "0"
        
    cr = details["Content Rating"] if "Content Rating" in details else "Not Yet Rated"
    if cr == " Not Yet Rated":
        cr = "NA"
    else:
        cr = details["Content Rating"].split(" ", 2)[1]
        
    data = {
        "year": year,
        "title": details["Drama"] if "Drama" in details else "",
        "synopsis": cleanSynopsis,
        "epsCount": details["Episodes"] if "Episodes" in details else "",
        "country": details["Country"] if "Country" in details else "",
        "website": link,
        "watcherCount": details["Watchers"] if "Watchers" in details else "",
        "akaTitle": aka,
        "genre": genre,
        "tags": tags,
        "airedDate": details["Aired"] if "Aired" in details else "",
        "ogNetwork": details["Original Network"] if "Original Network" in details else "",
        "epDuration": details["Duration"] if "Duration" in details else "",
        "score": score,
        "ranked":re.search('\d+', details["Ranked"]).group(0) if "Ranked" in details else "",
        "popularity":re.search('\d+', details["Popularity"]).group(0) if "Popularity" in details else "",
        "contentRating": cr,
        "where2Watch": w2w,
        "top6cast": cnc
    }
    
    return data

for page in range(1, int(lastNumPage)+1):
    urlIn = url + "?page=" + str(page)
    GetDrama(urlIn)

df = pd.DataFrame(dramalist)
df.to_csv('dramalist.csv', index=False)

Recommendation System¶

I carefully constructed a dataframe containing essential data, including titles, genres, tags, and the top six casts. In the initial test, I employed the Count Vectorizer to explore the feasibility of developing an accurate recommendation system. The second test involves utilizing the TfidfTransformer to further enhance the recommendation system's performance and accuracy. By employing these techniques, I aim to create a robust and efficient recommendation system that can suggest relevant and personalized drama titles to users based on their interests and preferences.

#Clean data by removing spaces and setting to lowercase
def clean_data(row):
    if isinstance(row, list):
        return [str.lower(i.replace(" ", "")) for i in row]
    else:
        if isinstance(row, str):
            return str.lower(row.replace(" ", ""))
        else:
            return ""
        
features = ['genre', 'tags', 'top6cast']
for feature in features:
    dramalist_df[feature] = dramalist_df[feature].apply(clean_data)

The collected data is utilized to calculate the similarity between dramas. The "soup" data, containing relevant information such as genres, tags, and top six casts, undergoes preprocessing and is converted into a vectorizer. By employing the cosine similarity score, we can then measure the similarity between two vectors, ultimately enabling us to recommend relevant and personalized drama titles based on users' preferences and interests. This approach ensures that users receive tailored recommendations, enhancing their overall viewing experience.

get_recommendation function is designed to take the name of a drama and the similarity function as input parameters. Utilizing the similarity function, it computes the similarity scores between the specified drama and other dramas in the dataset. The function then retrieves a list of these similarity scores, enumerates the tuples, and sorts them in descending order based on the similarity score. Finally, the function selects the top 10 recommendations and returns the list, allowing users to receive personalized and relevant drama recommendations based on their selected drama.

def get_recommendations(title, cosine_sim=cosine_sim2):
    idx = indices[title]
    similarity_scores = list(enumerate(cosine_sim[idx]))
    similarity_scores = sorted(similarity_scores, reverse=True)
    similarity_scores = similarity_scores[1:11]
    drama_indices = [ind[0] for ind in similarity_scores]
    dramas = dramalist_df['title'].iloc[drama_indices]
    return dramas

print(get_recommendations("Hidden Love", cosine_sim2))

In the second test, the TFIDFTransformer is employed to determine similarities between dramas. The "soup" data is processed using the TFIDFTransformer. This technique calculates the importance of each term in the "soup" data by considering its frequency in the document and across all documents. We can enhance the recommendation system's accuracy and provide more refined and tailored drama recommendations to users based on their interests and preferences.

#create a "soup" containing all the metadata extracted for vectorizer use
def create_soup2(features):
    return ' '.join(features['top6cast']) + ' ' + ' '.join(features['tags']) + ' ' + ' '.join(features['genre'])

dramalist_df["soup2"] = dramalist_df.apply(create_soup2, axis=1)
print(dramalist_df["soup2"].head())

#Create a normalized function to normalize the words in description
stemmer = SnowballStemmer("english", ignore_stopwords=False)
def normalized(X):
    normalized = []
    for x in X:
        words = nltk.word_tokenize(x)
        words = [word.lower() for word in words]
        normalized.append(' '.join([stemmer.stem(word) for word in words if re.match('[a-zA-Z]+', word)]))
    return normalized

#create a tfidf matrix of the normalized token/word
pipe = Pipeline([
    ('normalize', FunctionTransformer(normalized, validate=False)),
    ('counter_vectorizer', CountVectorizer(
        max_df=0.9, max_features=20000,
        min_df=0.1, stop_words='english',
        ngram_range=(1,3)
    )),
    ('tfidf_transform', TfidfTransformer())
])

tfidf_matrix = pipe.fit_transform([x for x in dramalist_df['soup2']])

similarity_distance = cosine_similarity(tfidf_matrix)

dramalist_df.index = dramalist_df.index.drop_duplicates(keep="first")

#create function to find similar games
def find_similar(title):
    index = dramalist_df[dramalist_df['title'] == title].index[0]
    similarity_score = list(enumerate(similarity_distance[index]))
    similarity_score = sorted(similarity_score, key=lambda x:x[1], reverse=True)
    similarity_score = similarity_score[2:17]
    drama_index = [ind[0] for ind in similarity_score] 
    most_similar = dramalist_df.iloc[drama_index, 1]
    return most_similar

print("Top 15 Recommendations")
print(find_similar('Move to Heaven'))
